One of the major buckets of work we identified under the broader risk factor readiness program is the Risk Factor Eligibility Test, or RFET.

The purpose of RFET is simple to say, but difficult to execute: it allows us to classify each risk factor as modellable or non-modellable.

But in the deep-dive session, before we even got into the mechanics of the framework, some very important questions were raised.

Do we actually capture every risk factor?

Is the list complete?

Is this a one-time classification exercise, or does it need to be dynamic?

What happens when a desk expands into a new product, a new instrument, or a new pricing model?

And more importantly, what would regulators expect us to demonstrate?

The answer became clear: we cannot start only from a static risk factor list and assume it is complete.

We need to start from the source of economic truth: the market data used by the Front Office pricer.

If a market data object is used by the pricer to value positions, then we need to understand whether it maps to a risk factor, whether it is already captured in risk, whether it is proxied, or whether it is only a pricing input and not a true market risk factor.

That mapping between Front Office market data objects and Risk risk factors becomes the foundation of the RFET framework.

It gives us coverage.

It gives us traceability.

And it gives us a way to prove that we are not missing important drivers of P&L and capital.

For the initial deep dive, we focused on Rates and FX because those areas are in relatively better shape, with most of the data residing in Vasara and MDSOR.

Even in these better-controlled asset classes, the mapping exercise gave us very useful insights.

First, we found market data objects that are properly mapped to relevant risk factors. These are the clean cases. They are the natural candidates to bring into RFET because we can trace the pricing input to the risk representation.

Second, we found market data objects that are used in pricing but are not currently mapped to any risk factor. Examples include items such as correlation inputs, derived data, filled history, proxy-based series, and certain spreads used in bond futures.

That is important because it shows that RFET is not only a pass/fail test. It is also a discovery mechanism. It tells us where risk may exist in pricing but may not yet be fully represented in the risk factor framework.

Third, we found pricing inputs that are relevant for valuation but do not necessarily require a standalone risk factor. Examples include fixings, reset costs, or operational pricing inputs. This distinction matters because we do not want to over-engineer the risk factor universe. We need to separate true market risk drivers from valuation mechanics.

Fourth, and probably most importantly, we found cases where the Front Office market data and the Risk representation are disconnected. For example, an instrument may be priced using one curve, while risk represents it using a different curve or a different configuration. In agency bonds, for example, this raises the question of whether the correct risk representation should be Treasury-based or sovereign/government-bond-based.

That is not just a data mapping issue. That becomes a model-alignment issue.

So the key message from the deep dive is this:

RFET cannot be treated as a one-time regulatory classification exercise.

It has to become a dynamic control framework that starts from every market data object used in pricing, maps it to risk factors, identifies gaps, explains proxies, and continuously refreshes the modellability status as products, desks, and market data evolve.

The value of this work is bigger than just saying “modellable” or “non-modellable.”

It gives us a way to show regulators that we understand what drives our P&L, that we have a controlled process to identify missing or weak risk factors, and that we can defend the connection between pricing, risk, and capital.

The punchline is:

We are not just building an RFET engine.

We are building the evidence layer that proves our risk factor universe is complete, explainable, dynamic, and defensible.
